    </exercise><exercise id="fs-id1653384" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2194900">    <para id="import-auto-id1168465430113">There are two important isotopes of uranium— <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mtext>235</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mtext>238</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>; these isotopes are nearly identical chemically but have different atomic masses. Only <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mtext>235</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is very useful in nuclear reactors. One of the techniques for separating them (gas diffusion) is based on the different average velocities <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>rms</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> of uranium hexafluoride gas, <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>UF</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math>. (a) The molecular masses for <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mtext>235</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>UF</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mtext>238</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msub><m:mtext>UF</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> are 349.0 g/mol and 352.0 g/mol, respectively. What is the ratio of their average velocities? (b) At what temperature would their average velocities differ by 1.00 m/s? (c) Do your answers in this problem imply that this technique may be difficult? </para></problem></exercise>
